Module 1: Introduction to the Visualization Analysis¶

Visualization Analysis in Python¶

Visualization analysis in Python refers to the process of examining data visually to understand it better and extract useful insights from it. It involves creating graphical representations of data, such as charts, graphs, and maps, to make it easier to identify patterns, trends, and outliers within large datasets. Visualization is an essential component of data analysis and data science, as it helps to communicate complex data in a clear and understandable manner.

Libraries for Visualization in Python:¶

  1. Matplotlib: It is the most widely used data visualization library in Python. It allows for the creation of static, animated, and interactive visualizations in Python.
  2. Seaborn: Built on top of Matplotlib, Seaborn is a statistical plotting library that provides a high-level interface for drawing attractive and informative statistical graphics.
  3. Plotly: Plotly is a library that allows users to create interactive plots that can be embedded in web pages or used in data analysis.
  4. Bokeh: Bokeh is another library for creating interactive and real-time streaming content.
  5. Pandas Plotting: Pandas itself has built-in methods for data visualization. Each of these libraries has its own strengths and weaknesses, and the best one to use depends on the specific task and requirements.

Seaborn¶

Seaborn is indeed a popular statistical data visualization library built on top of Matplotlib. It was developed to simplify and enhance the capabilities of Matplotlib, making it easier and quicker to create visually appealing and informative plots. Seaborn provides a high-level interface and various built-in functions for creating various statistical visualizations, making it more accessible to users, especially those working with complex datasets.

Key features of Seaborn include:

  • Improved default styles: Seaborn comes with enhanced default styles and color palettes.

  • High-level functions: Seaborn offers a set of high-level functions for creating common statistical plots. These functions often require less code compared to Matplotlib.

  • Built-in statistical visualizations: Seaborn provides statistical plots that incorporate data analysis and visualization, such as regression plots, and kernel density estimation plots.

  • Tight integration with Pandas: Seaborn is designed to work with Pandas DataFrames.

  • Flexible customization

In [3]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

titanic = sns.load_dataset("titanic")
sns.stripplot(data = titanic, x = "sex", y = "age")
plt.show()

The stripplot( ) function takes the two features in the dataset that we want to visualize. It is similar to the scatter plot, but they are often used when one variable is categorical instead of when both variables are continuous.

  • You may notice that when producing visualizations with Seaborn, labels within your dataframe are applied to their respective categories.
  • This is an improvement over Matplotlib, as it was required that you manually labeled the X-axis with your desired labels.
  • You must make sure that your dataframe should have clearly defined column names with spcified datatypes.

Exercise 2 Figure Scaling¶

You can adjust the size of plots to fit various presentation settings with Seaborn. Additionally, Seaborn provides the option to change the "context" of a plot, which can modify its size and shape to suit different presentation formats better.

For example, you can set the context for notebooks, conference talks, or papers. This is an example of figure customization.

In [4]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

titanic = sns.load_dataset("titanic")

sns.set(context = "paper")

sns.stripplot(data = titanic, x = "sex", y = "age")
plt.show()
In [5]:

Change kde = True to show the KDE:

Kernel Density Estimation (KDE) is a statistical method used to estimate the probability density function of a continuous variable. It smoothens the distribution of data points by placing a kernel (usually a Gaussian function) on each data point and summing the contributions from all data points to create a smooth curve.

In [9]:
sns.histplot(diamonds_df.carat, kde = True)
Out[9]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='carat', ylabel='Count'>

# get records in the DataFrame corresponding to ideal cut
ideal_group = diamonds_df.loc[diamonds_df['cut']=='Ideal']

# get the location of x coordinate where the annotation has to be placed
x = ideal_group.index.tolist()[0]

# get the location of y coordinate where the annotation has to be placed
y = len(ideal_group)

# print the x and y co-ordinates:
print(x)
print(y)

0
21551

Next, we will annotate the plot with a note:

In [27]:
# annotate the plot with any note or extra information

# Generate a bar plot using catplot function of the seaborn library:
ax = sns.catplot(x = "cut", 
                 data = diamonds_df, 
                 aspect = 1.5, 
                 kind = "count",
                 color = "blue")

plt.annotate('excellent polish and symmetry ratings;\nreflects almost all the light that enters it', 
             xy = (x,y), 
             xytext = (x + 0.3, y + 2000),
             arrowprops = dict(facecolor = 'red'))

plt.show()

This code is a part of Matplotlib library in Python, used for annotating a point (x, y) on a plot. Let's break down the components:

plt.annotate(): This function is used to annotate the point xy with the text.

  • text: The first parameter is the text that will be used for annotation. In this case, it's a string explaining that the point represents excellent polish and symmetry ratings.

  • xy: This parameter is a tuple representing the coordinates of the point that you want to annotate. (x, y) are the coordinates of the point to be annotated.

  • xytext: This parameter is a tuple representing the coordinates where the annotation text will be placed on the plot. In this case, the text will be placed slightly to the right (x + 0.3) and above (y + 2000) the annotated point.

  • arrowprops: This parameter is used to draw an arrow from the text to the point. The facecolor is set to 'red', meaning the arrow will be red in color.

So, this code will place an annotation with a red arrow on a plot, pointing from the text to a specific point (x, y), and the text will explain that the point represents excellent polish and symmetry ratings.

Exercise 9 Creating a Static Hexagonal Binning Plot¶

In this exercise, we will generate a hexagonal binning plot to get a better understanding of the relationship between weight and mileage (mpg). Let's go through the following steps:

In [32]:
import seaborn as sns

mpg_df = sns.load_dataset("mpg")

## set the plot style to include ticks on the axes.
sns.set(style="ticks")
## hexbin plot
sns.jointplot(x = mpg_df.weight, 
              y = mpg_df.mpg, 
              kind = "hex",
              color = "#4CB391")
Out[32]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.JointGrid at 0x7fea3d99cdc0>
  • As you might notice, the histogram on the top and right axes depict the variance in the features represented by the x and y axes respectively (mpg and weight, in this example).
  • Also, you might have noticed in the previous scatter plot that data points overlapped heavily in certain areas, obscuring the actual distribution of the features. Hexbin plots are quite a nice data visualization tool when data points are very dense.

Exercise 10 Creating a Static Contour Plot¶

In this exercise, we'll create a contour plot to show the relationship between weight and mileage in the mpg dataset. We'll be able to see that the relationship between weight and mileage is strongest when there are more data points. Let's go through the following steps:

In [33]:
import seaborn as sns

mpg_df = sns.load_dataset("mpg")

# Contour plot
sns.set_style("white")
# Generate KDE plot
sns.kdeplot(x = mpg_df.weight, 
            y = mpg_df.mpg, 
            shade = True)
Out[33]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='weight', ylabel='mpg'>

Notice that the interpretation of contour plots is similar to that of hexbin plots – darker regions indicate more data points and lighter regions indicate fewer data points.

Exercise 11 Creating a Static Line Plot¶

In this exercise, we will create a scatter plot for a different pair of features, model_year and mpg. Then, we'll generate a line plot based on those discrete attributes – model_year and mpg. To do so, let's go through the following steps:

In [34]:
import seaborn as sns

mpg_df = sns.load_dataset("mpg")
# contour plot
sns.set_style("white")
# seaborn 2-D scatter plot
ax1 = sns.scatterplot(x = "model_year", 
                      y = "mpg", 
                      data = mpg_df)

In this example, we see that the model_year feature only takes discrete values between 70 and 82. Now, when we have a discrete numerical feature like this (model_year), drawing a line plot joining the data points is a good idea. We can draw a simple line plot showing the relationship between model_year and mileage with the following code.

In [35]:
# Draw a simple line plot to show the relationship between model_year 
# and mileage:
ax = sns.lineplot(x = "model_year", 
                  y = "mpg", 
                  data = mpg_df)

As we can see, the points connected by the solid line represent the mean of the y axis feature at the corresponding x coordinate. The shaded area around the line plot shows the confidence interval for the y axis feature (by default, seaborn sets this to a 95% confidence interval).

In [36]:
# Change the confidence interval to 68
sns.lineplot(x = "model_year", 
             y = "mpg", 
             data = mpg_df, 
             ci = 68)
Out[36]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='model_year', ylabel='mpg'>

ax = sns.lineplot(x="year", y="passengers", data=flights_df[flights_df['month']=='Jul'], color='grey')
ax = sns.lineplot(x="year", y="passengers", data=flights_df[flights_df['month']=='Aug'], color='yellow')
ax = sns.lineplot(x="year", y="passengers", data=flights_df[flights_df['month']=='Sep'], color='turquoise')
ax = sns.lineplot(x="year", y="passengers", data=flights_df[flights_df['month']=='Oct'], color='orange')
ax = sns.lineplot(x="year", y="passengers", data=flights_df[flights_df['month']=='Nov'], color='darkgreen')
ax = sns.lineplot(x="year", y="passengers", data=flights_df[flights_df['month']=='Dec'], color='darkred')

Creating line plots for each month in the flights_df DataFrame, plotting year against passengers. The code can be made more concise and efficient by using a loop to iterate over the months and colors, rather than repeating the sns.lineplot() function for each month. Below is the revised version of the code:

In [39]:
import seaborn as sns
flights_df = sns.load_dataset("flights")

# List of months and corresponding colors
months = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']
colors = ['green', 'red', 'blue', 'cyan', 'pink', 'black', 'grey', 'yellow', 'turquoise', 'orange',
          'darkgreen', 'darkred']

# Iterating over months and colors to create line plots
for month, color in zip(months, colors):
    ax = sns.lineplot(
        x="year", 
        y="passengers", 
        data=flights_df[flights_df['month'] == month], 
        color=color
    )

This approach reduces redundancy and makes the code more maintainable and readable.

Exercise 14 Histogram Revisited¶

This histogram shows the distribution of the weight feature along with the mean and median. Notice that the mean is not equal to the median, which means that the feature is not normally distributed.

In [42]:
 # histogram using seaborn
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import numpy as np

mpg_df = sns.load_dataset("mpg")
ax = sns.histplot(mpg_df.weight, 
                  bins = 50, 
                  kde = False)

# `label` defines the name used in legend
plt.axvline(x = np.mean(mpg_df.weight), 
            color = 'red', 
            label = 'mean')
plt.axvline(x = np.median(mpg_df.weight), 
            color = 'orange',
            label = 'median')
plt.legend(loc = 'upper right')
plt.show()

Exercise 15 Creating and Exploring a Static Box Plot¶

In this exercise, we will create a box plot to analyze the relationship between model_ year and mileage using the mpg dataset. We'll analyze manufacturing efficiency and the mileage of vehicles over a period of years. To do so, let's go through the following steps:

In [43]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

mpg_df = sns.load_dataset("mpg")
# box plot: mpg(mileage) vs model_year
sns.boxplot(x = 'model_year', 
            y = 'mpg', 
            data = mpg_df)
plt.show()

Notice that the mileage improved substantially in the 80s compared to the 70s. Let's add another feature to our mpg DataFrame that denotes whether the car was manufactured in the 70s or 80s.

Modify the mpg DataFrame by creating a new feature, model_decade:

mpg_df['model_decade'] = np.floor(mpg_df.model_year/10)*10
mpg_df['model_decade'] = mpg_df['model_decade'].astype(int)

Exercise 16 Creating a Static Violin Plot¶

In this exercise, we will use the mpg dataset and generate a violin plot depicting the detailed variation of mileage (mpg) based on model_decade and region of origin:

In [47]:
import seaborn as sns
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

mpg_df = sns.load_dataset("mpg")

# creating the feature 'model_decade'
mpg_df['model_decade'] = np.floor(mpg_df.model_year/10)*10
mpg_df['model_decade'] = mpg_df['model_decade'].astype(int)

# code for violinplots
sns.violinplot(x = 'model_decade', 
               y = 'mpg', 
               data = mpg_df, 
               hue = 'origin')
plt.show()
  • We can see here that, during the 70s, while most vehicles in the US had a median mileage of 19 mpg, vehicles in Japan and Europe had median mileages of around 27 and 25 mpg.
  • While the mileages of vehicles in Europe and Japan jumped by 7 to 8 points in the 80s, the median mileage of vehicles in the US was still similar to that of the vehicles in Japan and Europe in the previous decade.

Exercise 17 Correlation Plots¶

Correlation plots are a really useful type of plot that allows you to visualize and explore the relationship between many different variable and a target variable. Let's go ahead and create a correlation plot using Seaborn:

In [48]:
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

file = pd.read_csv('AmesHousing.csv')
# Dropping some variables that aren't important
file.drop(['Order', 'PID'], axis = 1, inplace = True)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (10, 14))
saleprice_corr = file.corr()[['SalePrice']]
sns.heatmap(saleprice_corr,
          annot = True,
          ax = ax)
plt.show()

Now, this isn't very ordered and it would be easier on the eyes if this was sorted. Let's sort this before plotting:

In [49]:
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

file = pd.read_csv('AmesHousing.csv')
# Dropping some variables that aren't important
file.drop(['Order', 'PID'], axis = 1, inplace = True)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (10, 14))
saleprice_corr = file.corr()[['SalePrice']]

# Sorting 
sorted_saleprice_corr = saleprice_corr.sort_values(by = 'SalePrice', 
                                                   ascending = False)

sns.heatmap(sorted_saleprice_corr, annot = True, ax = ax)
plt.show()

Exercise 18 Pair Plots¶

Pairwise relationship can be displayed through the use of the pairplot( ) function, which shows possible pairs for each of the variables in the dataset and a univariate plot along the diagonal:

In [50]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

iris = sns.load_dataset("iris")
sns.pairplot(iris, hue = 'species')
plt.show()

Here, we've just set the hue to reflect the species from the Iris Dataset. By default, Seaborn chooses a plot type that seems fitting for the given dataset. In this case, it is a scatter plot, with kde plots in the diagonal line.

Exercise 19 Change Pair Plot Kind¶

Let's change the kind argument so that the Pair Plot uses a different type of plot instead of Scatter Plots for non-diagonal comparisons.

These changes will only change the type of info we get, since histograms are very complementary with KDE plots, and Regression Plots are complementary to Scatter Plots:

In [51]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

iris = sns.load_dataset("iris")
sns.pairplot(iris, 
             hue = 'species',
             kind = 'reg',
             diag_kind = 'hist')
plt.show()

Or, we could use KDE as the main kind, and just let Seaborn choose the diagonal plots automatically:

In [52]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

iris = sns.load_dataset("iris")
sns.pairplot(iris, 
             hue = 'species',
             kind = 'kde',
             diag_kind = 'auto')
plt.show()

Other than kde, reg, and scatter, you can also set the main kind to hist:

In [53]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

iris = sns.load_dataset("iris")
sns.pairplot(iris, 
             hue = 'species',
             kind = 'hist')
plt.show()
